        <section class="prose">
          <h2>How to translate English to Pig Latin</h2>
          <p>Pig Latin is a playful language game where you disguise English words by moving sounds around. It’s popular in classrooms, games, and puzzles.</p>
          <p>This translator automates the rules so you can convert whole paragraphs instantly, without losing punctuation or capitalization.</p>

          <h3>Core rules (standard Pig Latin)</h3>
          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1">
              <li><strong>Words starting with a vowel (A, E, I, O, U)</strong><br>
                Add <code>yay</code> (or <code>way</code>, depending on your setting) to the end.
                <br>Examples:
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4">
                  <li><code>apple</code> → <code>appleyay</code></li>
                  <li><code>orange</code> → <code>orangeyay</code></li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Words starting with a consonant or consonant cluster</strong><br>
                Move all leading consonants to the end, then add <code>ay</code>.
                <br>Examples:
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4">
                  <li><code>dog</code> → <code>ogday</code></li>
                  <li><code>smile</code> → <code>ilesmay</code> (sm + ile)</li>
                  <li><code>chair</code> → <code>airchay</code> (ch + air)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Capitalization and punctuation</strong><br>
                The translator:
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4">
                  <li>keeps commas, periods, and question marks in place</li>
                  <li>preserves ALL CAPS and Title Case</li>
                  <li>leaves numbers and symbols unchanged</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <h3>Examples</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><code>Hello, world!</code> → <code>Ellohay, orldway!</code></li>
            <li><code>This is a secret message.</code> → <code>Isthay isyay ayay ecretsay essagemay.</code></li>
            <li><code>PROGRAMMING is fun</code> → <code>OGRAMMINGPRay isyay unfay</code></li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Tips for using the Pig Latin translator</h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Choose your dialect:</strong> Use the “Vowel rule” dropdown to switch between <code>yay</code> and <code>way</code> styles.</li>
            <li><strong>Toggle Y as a vowel:</strong> When enabled, words like <code>yellow</code> treat <code>y</code> as a vowel in some positions.</li>
            <li><strong>Round-trip check:</strong> Translate English → Pig Latin, then switch direction and translate back to see how reversible your text is.</li>
            <li><strong>Use for games and teaching:</strong> Great for language lessons, secret notes, or just having fun with friends.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Limitations</h2>
          <p>Pig Latin is not a real language, so there isn’t a single “official” rule set. This tool follows a common schoolyard variant and makes reasonable guesses when translating back to English, but some ambiguous words or invented slang may not reverse perfectly.</p>

          <h2>FAQ</h2>
          <h3>Can I translate long texts?</h3>
          <p>Yes. The translator runs entirely in your browser and can handle long paragraphs. Extremely large texts may be slower, but there is no strict character limit.</p>

          <h3>Does it support other languages?</h3>
          <p>The rules are designed for English spelling and pronunciation. Text in other languages will still be processed, but the results may not follow any familiar Pig Latin convention.</p>
